if you run a go get command, as

{code}
#!bash

go get bitbucket-instance/aproject/arepo 
{code}

a GET on https://bitbucket-instance/aproject/arepo?go-get=1 is done on bitbucket.

bitbucket returns this body:

{code}
<!DOCTYPE html><html lang="en"><head><meta charset="utf-8"><meta name="go-import" content="bitbucket-instance/aproject/arepo git https://bitbucket-instance/scm/aproject/arepo.git"></head><body></body></html>
{code}

Is there a way to force a return with a Git URL with ssh and not https per default on repository ? This will be allow "go get" to clone repository over ssh and not https.

{code}
#!bash

$ hg push -b jahaziel
pushing to ssh://hg@bitbucket.org/juanefren/at_dev
searching for changes
remote: abort: abandoned transaction found!
remote: (run &#x27;hg recover&#x27; to clean up transaction)
abort: stream ended unexpectedly (got 0 bytes, expected 4)
{code}

It would be useful to have a notification if someone deletes a repository.

Under &#x27;Notifications&#x27; for a user&#x27;s settings : https://bitbucket.org/account/user/bobsmith/notifications/

There is a section that states &#x27;Email me about&#x27; and then a list :

* {code}
Someone mentioning me
{code}
* {code}
My access to a repository or a team changing
{code}
* {code}
Occasional updates from Bitbucket and Atlassian
{code}

It would be useful if there was an additional tickbox for:

* Someone deleting a repository.

Currently if someone deletes a repository then it silently disappears.

We have found that the PR Merge Check process for Approvals can be subverted by a non-author of the PR.

h1. How to recreate
# Set minimum approvals to 1;
# User 1 creates a pull request (User 1 is the Author);
# User 2 updates the PR with subversive changes;
# User 2 approves the PR and is then able to merge.

h1. Why is this bad?
User 2 can add subversive changes, approve and merge.

h1. What should happen?
The approval of a commit author should not count towards the merge check approval count.

